<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-347-958  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 347 958.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>CommunicationsWeek  April 16 1990 n296 p16(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Different Languages: problems/solutions. (United TechnologiesCorp. selects gateway service from Wiltek)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Bailie, James; Parnon, Thomas.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>United Technologies Corp, facing the task of coordinating itsheterogeneous network of minicomputers, mainframes, local areanetwork and electronic mail systems, turns to Wiltek Inc for aneconomical electronic-mail gateway solution.andP;  The $19 billioncompany, which sends over 5,000 e-mail, telex and facsimilemessages monthly to 100 international locations, determined that agateway based on its private X.25 network would be the best meansof assuring interoperability and reducing the costs ofcommunication.andP;  Wiltek Inc (Norwalk, CT) was selected largelybecause it offered a gateway service that did not require theinstallation of additional hardware or software to the UnitedTechnologies' mainframes and minicomputers.andP;  Wiltek's systemcreates 1,000 electronic mailboxes and assures connectivity.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   United Technologies Corp. (communication systems)Wiltek Inc. (contracts).andO;Ticker:    NWK; UTX; WLTK.andO;Topic:     Data CommunicationsElectronic Mail SystemsGateways (Connector)Network ManagementConnectivityContracts.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>